  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Making Home(s) in Displacement,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2021, addresses critical themes of home and belonging amidst forced displacement. With its focus on sustainability and policy relevance, the work aims to inform and influence sectoral practices, linking scholarly discussions to real-world applications.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Making Home(s) in Displacement\" explores the complexities of establishing a sense of home in the context of displacement. Published by Leuven University Press in 2021, the book has been noted for its linkage to commercial platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads, demonstrating its potential for reaching a broad audience beyond academic circles. Although it has yet to generate significant citation activity, its presence on these commercial sites suggests an opportunity for engagement with lay readers interested in migration issues.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work aligns with global sustainability goals, evidenced by its strong emphasis on policy relevance within its narratives. With one Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) linked to its themes, it contributes to broader conversations about sustainable living and refugee integration policies. This situates the book within important dialogues on international development and human rights, suggesting that its findings may have practical implications for policymakers and community organizations.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of high-fidelity social discourse metrics such as mentions on Wikipedia or threads on social media platforms, the commercial interest indicates a potential gap that could be bridged through targeted outreach strategies. Engaging with these platforms could foster a community dialogue around its themes, enhancing visibility and scholarly uptake over time.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while \"Making Home(s) in Displacement\" currently lacks widespread recognition within academic citations or community discussions, its thematic relevance to humanitarian issues and its commercial presence present avenues for future engagement. As discussions surrounding displacement and home continue to evolve, the work stands to offer valuable insights for multiple stakeholders involved in humanitarian and sociocultural efforts.</p>",
